<PB REF="1">
<P>THE LOVE OF GAIN: <HI>A POEM.</HI></P>
<P>IMITATED FROM THE THIRTEENTH SATIRE OF JUVENAL.</P>
<Q><L>Oh! thou &s;weet King-killer, and dear Divorce</L>
<L>'Twixt natural Son and Sire! thou bright Defiler</L>
<L>Of Hymen's pure&s;t Bed! thou valiant Mars!</L>
<L>Thou ever-loved, fre&s;h, young, and delicate Wooer,</L>
<L>Who&s;e blu&s;h doth thaw the con&s;ecrated &s;now</L>
<L>That lies on Dian's lap!</L>
<BIBL>SHAKESPEARE.</BIBL></Q>
<P>By M. G. LEWIS, ESQ. M. P. AUTHOR OF THE MONK, CASTLE-SPECTRE, ETC.</P>
<P><HI>LONDON:</HI> PRINTED FOR J. BELL, NO. 148, OXFORD-STREET.</P>
<P>1799.</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="dedication">
<PB REF="2">
<HEAD>TO THE HONOURABLE CHARLES JAMES FOX,</HEAD>
<P>THE following Lines are re&s;pectfully in&s;cribed, as a trifling Mark of the Veneration in which I hold his Talents and Character, and which his pre&s;ent Retirement from Public Life gives me an Opportunity thus to declare without running the Hazard of &s;ub|jecting my&s;elf to Party Cen&s;ure.</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>M. G. LEWIS.</SIGNED>
<DATE><HI>January</HI> 28<HI>th,</HI> 1799.</DATE></CLOSER>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="half title">
<PB REF="3">
<P>THE LOVE OF GAIN.</P>
</DIV1>
